column1: On 29 June 2018, how many public DC Fast Charge electric vehicle charging stations will be available in the United States?
column5: ['Less than 2,400', 'Between 2,400 and 2,700, inclusive', 'Between 2,701 and 3,100, inclusive', 'More than 3,100']
column6: ['Technology']
column11: The adoption of electric vehicles (EVs) is subject to a "chicken and egg" problem such that potential consumers are waiting for an extensive charging network and businesses are awaiting more electric cars on the roads to justify building more charging stations. This problem is especially relevant for DC Fast Charging stations that can fully charge the EV in less than 30 minutes. This question will be resolved using data from the U.S. Department of Energy's Alternative Fuels Data Center. Data on public DC Fast Charging stations can be found by clicking on "more search options" and selecting only "DC Fast" on the "Charger types" drop-down menu. The relevant number is "electric stations." Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help. As of 29 June there are 2,318 public DC Fast Charge electric vehicle charging stations available. This question closed as "Less than 2,400" with an end date of 29 June. See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated.

There seem to be built around 2000 charging stations per year. It was only half of that last year, but there are quite a few fluctuations, so we will go with a possibly slightly to high estimate of 2000 per year. Around 10% of the stations are DC stations, which would yield 200 of those built per year. However, it is likely that a significantly bigger perecentage of the new stations uses the new and better technology, and it could even be, that old stations are being replaced by newer DC ones. So i will go with an estimate of 40% of newly built stations being DC stations and arrive at 800 stations per year. The possible overestimation of the base rate hopefully cancels out with my ignorance of ongoing projects of VW, Tesla and the like to strengthen the infrastructure. So i arrive at a point estimate of 800/12*(4+2/3)=311 new stations until the deadline, which will most likely land in the lower 2400 - 2700 bracket. Looking at VWs plans in here, https://electrek.co/2017/04/14/vw-nationwide-150-kw-fast-charging-network-electric-vehicle/ large operations seen to take considerable planning time, why large Deviations up into the highest bracket seem very unlikely.

Based on the cost of installing these vs. others (much higher for DC Fast), the (presumed -- I didn't do enough research to back this up) higher cost of maintenance on gasoline pumps and the likelihood that older pumps would just not be replaced in favor of adding electric chargers. A gas station, hotel, corporate office park looking toward the future might add electric chargers as a result of the swing automakers are making toward electric. For offices it's a perk for businesses/their employees, and might also provide them some tax breaks (depending upon future policy and states). That said, I don't think the growth will necessarily accelerate yet, as the hope would be that the cost comes down first, before the tipping point. If I were considering installing, I might try to push it off a year or perhaps two to let the price drop, banking on the current administration not changing tax credits (I don't believe there is anything related in the current tax bill on the table)

After averaging the rate of new charging stations per in the United States, about 5,505 charging stations are added each year. Last year was a low year at 2,494. I hypothesize that this is not a sign of slowdown but I'm guessing that as Tesla and other new models from other manufactures (as sales are increasing, but I haven't explored that angle yet) will only drive the average upward in the remainder of the decade, and last's year slowdown will only means that the market needs to correct. By simply going with "guess same rate of change" which for the most part is a good strategy you're going to arrive at well over 3100.
Another drag on putting in charging stations is early obsolescence of the existing tech. Wireless charging is already available for the home that is close to an L2 station in terms of charging time.
